comp_sys_ibm_pc_hardware;From: jpw0@ns1.cc.lehigh.edu (JASON PAUL WALTERS) Subject: Re: GW2000 and SIMMS  In article <113956@bu.edu, nshah@acs2.bu.edu writes: I have a gateway2000 483/33 local bus system.  It has 4 slots for SIMMS that either have to use 4 or 16MB simms.  My question:  I just received a 4x9 70ns simm and it has ~30 pins.  The slot on the motherboard has at least 70 or so pins.  Did I get the wrong simm or can I still use my simm , although not all the pins on the slot would be flilled.  I have never encountered such a long slot for simms before. Anyone have suggestions?  I can't get a hold of Gateway yet.  Thanks Please post to the net or :   nshah@acs.bu.edu  Yes, You bought the WRONG SIMMS.....You need 1X36 or 4X36, which are 72 pin SIMMS.....These are better anyway becuase the send/receive data in 4byte (32bit+4bit parity, one for each byte) Chunks. You will undoubtedly see these SIMMS becoming more widely used in the near future.  Jason --                                       ****************************                                    *      Jason Walters       *                                    *     JPW0@LEHIGH.EDU      *                                    *JPW0@PL122.eecs.LEHIGH.EDU*                                    * a.k.a.   Modem Mouth     *
